Speaking
 to detectives, Mr Rockefeller reportedly insisted that faulty equipment
 aboard the train was to blame for the derailment because he was unable 
to slow down before a dangerous curve.

William Rockefeller Sr. defended his son to the New York Post, saying 'he’s one of the better engineers, the most dependable. And he really does like trains.'

The engineer's uncle, Jan Timothy Rockefeller, sounded a similar note in an interview with the New York Daily News, telling the paper that his nephew has always been very safety-conscious.  

'If he said the brakes failed, the brakes failed. He doesn’t lie,' Jan Rockefeller said.

